In the first of the three paragraphs quoted, Dante asserts that AEneas possessed a double nobility: a nobility proper to himself, and a nobility of inheritance, derived from ancestors and wives, In the second para- graph Dante proves that AEneas possessed a nobility proper to himself, alleging the qualities of justice and prowess ascribed to him by Virgil, together with Virgil’s statement that AEneas was not inferior to Hector.

In the rest of the chapter Dante proves that AEneas possessed a nobility of inheritance, the inheritance being itself double — through an· cestors and through wives, Each type of inheritance came to AEneas from each of the three continents As to ancestorS, Asia ennobled him through the more recent, such as Assaracus and others who ruled Phrygia3 Africa through Electra and Atlas; and Europe through Dar- danus· As to wiveS‚ Asia ennobled him through Creusa3 Africa through Did0; and Europe through Lavinia.
